Question 1: Problem Set A

Q1.1. Assume that n = 400 observations are independently drawn from a normal distribution with unknown population mean μ and unknown population variance σ2. The resulting sample, x’, is used to test H0 : μ ≤ 0 versus H1 : μ > 0 at significance level α = 0.05.

  1. What test should be used in this situation? If we observe x’ that results in x’ = 3.194887 and s2 = 104.0118, then what is the value of the test statistic?
  • Answer: Since the sample size is large we can use either z-test or t-test. however since s2 is given we use the t-test
t = (3.194887-0)/sqrt(104.0118/400)
t
## [1] 6.265333
  1. If we observe x’ that results in a test statistic value of 1.253067, then which of the following R expressions best approximates the significance probability?
  1. 2*pnorm(1.253067)
  2. 2*pnorm(-1.253067)
  3. 1-pnorm(1.253067)
  4. 1-pt(1.253067,df=399)
  5. pt(1.253067,df=399)
  • Answer: iii. 1-pnorm(1.253067) and iv. 1-pt(1.253067,df=399)
1-pnorm(1.253067)
## [1] 0.1050907
1-pt(1.253067,df=399)
## [1] 0.1054576
  1. True of False: if we observe x’ that results in a significance probability of p = 0.03044555, then we should reject the null hypothesis.
  • Answer: Significance level α = 0.05 , since p < α , the statement is true.

get_iqr = function (s){
q <- as.vector(quantile(s,probs=c(.25,.75)))
iqr <- q[2]-q[1]
return (iqr)
}

Construct a two-sided confidence interval for μ with a confidence coefficient of 1 − α = 0.90. Compare the results of these analyses to the results obtained in Section 10.4.

t = mean(CPA_log_vals) / (sd(CPA_log_vals)/sqrt(19))
1-pt(t,df=18)
## [1] 0.3635348
  • Answer: The p value 0.3635348 is much higher than the significance level of α = 0.05. So we dont reject the idea that the µ is less than equal to zero.
cf = c((mean(CPA_log_vals) - (qt(0.95,df=18) * (sd(CPA_log_vals)/sqrt(19)))),(mean(CPA_log_vals) + (qt(0.95,df=18) * (sd(CPA_log_vals)/sqrt(19)))))

Question: Set D

The ancient Greeks greatly admired rectangles with a height-to-width ratio of 1 : 1 + √5 / 2 = 0.618034. They called this number the “golden ratio” and used it repeatedly in their art and architecture, e.g., in building the Parthenon. Furthermore, golden rectangles are often found in the art of later western cultures. A cultural anthropologist wondered if the Shoshoni, a native American civilization, also used golden rectangles. The following measurements, which appear as Data Set 150 in A Handbook of Small Data Sets, are height-to width ratios of beaded rectangles used by the Shoshoni in decorating various leather goods:

0.693 0.662 0.690 0.606 0.570 0.749 0.672 0.628 0.609 0.844 0.654 0.615 0.668 0.601 0.576 0.670 0.606 0.611 0.553 0.933

We will analyze the Shoshoni rectangles as a 1-sample location problem.

Q3.1. There are two natural scales that we might use in analyzing these data. One possibility is to analyze the ratios themselves; the other is to analyze the (natural) logarithms of the ratios. For which of these possibilities would an assumption of normality seem more plausible? Please justify your answer.

  • Answer: Using logorithms for ratios, makes the distribution seem more prone to being normal. Hence the normality is more plausible for natural logorithms of ratios. If we observe the probability plots , we see that the plot for log values is symmetrically upwards, much more so than the plot without log.
x = c( 0.693, 0.662, 0.690, 0.606, 0.570,
0.749, 0.672, 0.628, 0.609, 0.844,
0.654, 0.615, 0.668, 0.601, 0.576,
0.670, 0.606, 0.611, 0.553, 0.933)
qqnorm(x)

qqnorm(log(x))

Q3.2. Choose the possibility (ratios or logarithms of ratios) for which an assumption of normality seems more plausible. Formulate suitable null and alternative hypotheses for testing the possibility that the Shoshoni were using golden rectangles. Using Student’s 1-sample t-test, compute a significance probability for testing these hypotheses. Would you reject or accept the null hypothesis using a significance level of 0.05?

  • Answer: We can take H0 : µ = (2/1+sqrt(5)), ie the Shoshini tribe used the golden rectangles. H1 : µ <> (2/1+sqrt(5))
m = 2/(1+sqrt(5))
t = (mean(x) - m ) / (sd(x) / sqrt(20))
2 * (1 - pt(abs(t), df = 19))
## [1] 0.0541156
m = 2/(1+sqrt(5))
t = (mean(log(x)) - log(m) ) / (sd(log(x)) / sqrt(20))
2 * (1 - pt(abs(t), df = 19))
## [1] 0.05771059
  • The p-value for both the cases is only slightly higher than 0.05, so accept the null hypothesis

Q4. A researcher wanted to see if live reggae music improved students’ math test scores. He selected a sample of 61 students from his university and gave them a math test. The students then studied for two and a half hours while an acoustic reggae band played quietly. The students then took another math test of the same difficulty. The researcher’s variable was the change in test score for each student - a positive change meant the student did better after listening to reggae, while a negative change meant a student did worse. He found that the changes had an approximately normal distribution with mean 6.5 and standard deviation 12. a. Assuming the sample is random, test the hypothesis that the population average is positive.

  • Answer: H0: µ => 0, H1: µ < 0
z = (6.5 - 0) / (12/sqrt(61))
pnorm(z)
## [1] 0.9999883
  1. Does the study provide convincing evidence that live reggae music improves students’ math test scores? Explain why or why not.
  • Answer: Since the p-value is very high, we can say that the study provides convincing evidence that live reggae music improves students’ math test scores
